      <div xml:id="NA175-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu (EN, ER, ET, EV: tōḻi) ciṟaippuṟamākac colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what is said when [HE] was behind the fence.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA175">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            neṭuṅkaṭa lalaitta koṭuntimiṟ paratavar</l>
<l>            koḻumīṉ koḷḷai yaḻimaṇaṟ kuvaii</l>
<l>            mīṉe yaṭṭik kiḷiñcil pottiya</l>
<l>            ciṟutī viḷakkiṟ ṟuñcu naṟumalarp</l>
<l>            puṉṉai yōṅkiya tuṟaivaṉō ṭaṉṉai </l>
<l>            tāṉaṟin taṉṟō vilaḷē pāṉāṭ</l>
<l>            cēriyam peṇṭir ciṟuco ṉampic</l>
<l>            cuṭuvāṉ pōla nōkku</l>
<l>            maṭupā laṉṉaveṉ pacalai meyyē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Was it known<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṉṉai aṟintaṉṟō ilaḷē</term>: again we see the perfective neuter singular used in negation as a verbal noun (cf. note on NA 27.6). Here, however, we are also confronted with a particle marking which seems to demand two sentences (which is by no means an isolated case; cf. NA 193.5, 239.9). It seems possible to try this way: "as for mother knowing ..., she does not."</note> to mother herself,</l>
<l rend="indent">[our connection?]<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tuṟaivaṉoṭu</term> is asyndetic again. Perhaps we have to assume an ellipsis of the above kind.</note> with the man from the ghat</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the Puṉṉai trees are high, with fragrant blossoms,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the fishermen,</l>
<l rend="indent3">with [their] bent boats that disturbed the long sea,</l>
<l rend="indent2">heap in the soft(?)<note place="foot">Soft - is that what <term xml:lang="ta">aḻi</term> is supposed to mean in connection with sand?</note> sand [their] catch of rich fish [and] sleep</l>
<l rend="indent3">by small-flamed lamps that are lighted in shells by pouring fish oil?</l>
<l rend="indent4">Not to her. At midday,</l>
<l rend="indent2">trusting in the belittling words<note place="foot">Thus the interpretation of <term xml:lang="ta">ciṟumoḻi</term> given by the old commentator on a parallel in PN 72.7, where <term xml:lang="ta">ciṟu col colliya</term> is glossed as <term xml:lang="ta">pulliya vārttaikaḷai kūṟiya</term> by the old commentary and as <term xml:lang="ta">pukaḻ koṉṟ’ uraittal</term> by Cam. (with reference to Pēr. on TP 258).</note> of the women in the quarter,</l>
<l>she looked, like the glowing sky(?),</l>
<l rend="indent">at my pallorous body, resembling boiled milk.</l>
        </lg>
